This video was produced by YT Wochit Vote It using http://wochit.com...
Apple has been given a court order to hack into the I-Phone of one of the San Bernardino shooters. But Apple CEO Tim Cook is fighting the judge\'s ruling to break into the shooters phone. 

FBI agents obtained legal permission to retrieve data from San Bernardino Shooter, Syed Rizwan Farook\'s I-Phone. But thanks to an Apple security feature, the agency hasn\'t been able to access the phone without wiping the data. That\'s because the I -Phone\'s have a security feature that wipes all the data after 10 failed passcode attempts and the FBI could risk loosing all possible critical information. 

In a public letter, Cook wrote that the court order to help the agency is a dangerous breach of privacy. \"They are not asking apple to redesign its product or to create a new backdoor to one of their products. They\'re simply asking for something that would have an impact on this one device,\" said White House Press Secretary, Josh Earnest in a press conference earlier this week.

WVUA 23 spoke with a Criminal Justice Professor and Academic Director of the Joint Electronic Crimes Task Force at the University of Alabama, Diana Dolliver to get a better grasp about this particular case and what Apple has to do to defend themselves along with what the outcome might be if the company doesn\'t cooperate with the court order and the FBI.

Dolliver said, the argument to the right to privacy and encryption doesn\'t really apply to this case. \"In the case of terrorism or criminals they don\'t have that reasonable expectation to privacy that you and I do and so that\'s the point of the court.\"

